---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import ExternalLink from "@/components/ExternalLink.astro";
import StatusBadge from "@/components/StatusBadge.astro";
import TagList from "@/components/TagList.astro";
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const project = (await getCollection("projects")).find(
  (entry) => entry.data.slug === "career-intelligence",
);
if (!project) {
  throw new Error("Missing Career Intelligence project entry");
}
---

<BaseLayout
  title={project.data.title}
  description={project.data.summary}
  canonicalPath="/projects/career-intelligence/"
>
  <section class="page-section container text-page">
    <p class="eyebrow">Project</p>
    <h1>{project.data.title}</h1>
    <p class="lede">{project.data.summary}</p>
    <div class="button-row">
      <StatusBadge status={project.data.status} accent={project.data.accent} />
      {
        project.data.repositoryUrl && (
          <ExternalLink href={project.data.repositoryUrl} label="Repository" />
        )
      }
    </div>
    <TagList tags={project.data.tags} />

    <h2>Project overview</h2>
    <p>
      Career Intelligence is a system for reasoning about careers as connected
      evidence, capabilities, preferences, and opportunities rather than
      reducing a person to a static resume.
    </p>

    <p>
      The public repository frames it as a source-backed career reasoning
      engine. Evidence, role matching, person-model reasoning, and generated
      materials stay separated so resumes and interview prep remain grounded in
      what the data can support.
    </p>

    <h2>Why it exists</h2>
    <p>
      Career tools often flatten people into titles, keywords, and resume bullet
      points. Career Intelligence instead models relationships between evidence,
      capabilities, preferences, projects, and opportunities.
    </p>

    <h2>How it reasons</h2>
    <p>
      The current public slice starts with structured synthetic career data,
      validates it against a schema, ranks source-backed evidence, analyzes role
      fit, applies person-model boundaries, and generates conservative demo
      artifacts.
    </p>

    <div class="diagram" aria-label="Career Intelligence data flow">
      <div class="diagram-row">
        <div class="diagram-node">Structured evidence</div>
        <div class="diagram-node">Schema validation</div>
        <div class="diagram-node">Evidence ranking</div>
      </div>
      <div class="diagram-node center">Career reasoning layer</div>
      <div class="diagram-row">
        <div class="diagram-node">Match report</div>
        <div class="diagram-node">Positioning notes</div>
        <div class="diagram-node">Interview prep</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Current capabilities</h2>
    <ul class="quiet-list split-list">
      <li>Public synthetic data model and schema validation</li>
      <li>Source-backed evidence ranking</li>
      <li>Role match analysis</li>
      <li>Positioning analysis</li>
      <li>Interview preparation analysis</li>
      <li>Conservative resume rendering helpers</li>
      <li>Generated synthetic demo artifacts</li>
      <li>Public visualization output</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What it explores</h2>
    <p>
      The interesting question is not only whether a person matches a job
      description. It is whether a system can preserve the evidence behind a
      career story, surface transferable skills, keep caveats visible, and use a
      person model without turning reflection-only claims into resume claims.
    </p>

    <h2>Status and links</h2>
    <p>
      Career Intelligence is active and public-safe. The current public repo
      contains the generic engine slice, schema, templates, default
      configuration, deterministic demo workflow, and fully synthetic Andy Barks
      example. It does not claim automated application submission, recruiter
      outreach, production users, or performance metrics.
    </p>
    <div class="button-row">
      {
        project.data.repositoryUrl && (
          <ExternalLink
            href={project.data.repositoryUrl}
            label="Career Intelligence repository"
          />
        )
      }
      <ExternalLink
        href="https://github.com/haleyparks329/career-intelligence/tree/main/examples/andy-barks/generated"
        label="Synthetic demo outputs"
      />
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
